{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e32fbc3f-67c3-4ddb-b607-4d3bf2cdb19b","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — re-installs the **same versions** already recorded. It fixes corrupted or partially-installed workloads but won't pull newer versions needed by a new SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK changed → versions are stale → use `update`. If workloads were the right version but files got corrupted, that's when you'd use `repair`.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf it still fails afterward, try a clean restore:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet clean\ndotnet restore\ndotnet build\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"27134ff3-2c04-4ffd-80e9-703df9a0a62c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general .NET knowledge question — I don't need to look at any files or run any commands.","outputTokens":281,"requestId":"1030:16EA54:15525B4:17E2E3F:69FD3379"},"id":"bc0d750b-cb30-432e-a848-e3bb3cfeb474","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:51:12.589Z","parentId":"052f6e91-ed97-493d-910e-65370661abdf"}
